        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>square-ended watercraft [300232716], symmetrical-ended watercraft [300232703], watercraft by end configuration [300232685], watercraft by form [300232663], watercraft by specific type [300219289], watercraft [300042940], vehicles (transportation) [300219258], Transportation Vehicles (hierarchy name) [300042929], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Small craft, traditionally clinker-built but more recently of plywood, with flat panels at each end instead of conventional posts; the panel at the bow is usually smaller than the one at the stern. For flat-bottomed, flat-sided, hard-chined inland watercraft, use "prams (bottom-based watercraft)."</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Úsese para embarcación pequeña, tradicionalmente construida de escoria, pero más recientemente de contrachapado, con paneles llanos en cada extremo en vez de los convencionales postes. El panel de la popa es generalmente más pequeño que el de la proa.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Te gebruiken voor kleine vaartuigen die traditiegetrouw overnaads gebouwd zijn, maar tegenwoordig ook van meerlagenhechthout worden gemaakt en aan beide kanten zijn voorzien van platte panelen in plaats van de meer gebruikelijke balken; het paneel aan de boeg is meestal kleiner dan die aan het achterdek.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099099/Van Dale groot woordenboek (1994)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>小型船，傳統上為魚鱗式外殼（clinker-built），但近代改為合板製作，兩端為平板而非常見的船艏柱及船艉柱，且船艏的平板通常小於船艉的平板。對於具平坦的船舷側面、銳稜泌線型（hard-chined）的內陸用平底船舶，則稱為「平艏船(坐底式船舶)」。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
